# Playwright Assertions
1️⃣ What are Assertions?
Assertions are used to verfiy that the appplication behaves as expected.
They check whether:
    1. an element is visible
    2. text is correct
    3. element is enabled or disabled
    4. checkbox is checked
    5. URL is correct
👉 If the condition passes → test passes
👉 If the condition fails → test fails
Simple meaning:
    Assertion = Verification in test automation

Example:
    expect(page.get_by_text("login")).to_be_visible()
This checks whether login text is visible on the page.

2️⃣ Why Assertions are Important
Assertions are important because they:
    1. Validate application behavior
    2. Ensure UI works correctly
    3. Detect bugs automatically
    4. Make automated tests meaningful
Without assertions:
    👉 Tests only perform actions but do not verify results.

3️⃣ Assertion Syntax in Playwright
Basic syntax:
    expect(locator).assertion()

Example:
    expect(page.locator("#login")).to_be_visible()

Example:
    expect(page.get_by_text("Dashboard")).to_be_visible()

4️⃣ Auto Waiting in Assertions
Playwright assertions automatically wait until the condition becomes true.
Example:
    expect(page.get_by_text("Login Successful")).to_be_visible()

Playwright will:
    1. Wait for the element
    2. Retry the assertion
    3. Fail only after timeout

Default timeout:
    5 seconds
this reduce flaky tests.

5️⃣ Commonly Used Assertions
These assertions are commonly used in projects and interviews.

6️⃣ Visibility Assertions
    1️⃣ to_be_visible()
    Checks whether element is visible
    Example:
        expect(page.get_by_text("Login")).to_be_visible()
    Meaning:
        1. Element exists
        2. Element visible on UI
    
    2️⃣ to_be_hidden()
    Checks whether element is hidden
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("#loading")).to_be_hidden()
    
7️⃣ Element State Assertions
    1️⃣ to_be_enabled()
    Checks if element is enabled
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("#submit")).to_be_enabled()
    
    2️⃣ to_be_disabled()
    Checks if element is disabled 
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("#submit")).to_be_disabled()
    
8️⃣ Checkbox Assertions
    1️⃣ to_be_checked()
    Checks whether checkbox or radio button is checked
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("#remember)).to_be_checked()

9️⃣ Text Assertions
    1️⃣ to_have_text()
    Checks exact text
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("hi)).to_have_text("Welcome")

    2️⃣ to_contain_text()
    Checks partial text
    Example:
        expect(page.locator(".message")).to_contain_text("Success")
    Example:
        expect(page.get_by_role("alert")).to_contain_text("Login successful")
    
🔟 Attribute Assertions
    1️⃣ to_have_attribute()
    Checks element attribute
    Example HTML
        <input type="text" disabled>
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("input")).to_have_attribute("type" , "text")

1️⃣1️⃣ Value Assertions
    1️⃣ to_have_value()
    Checks value inside input fields
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("#username")).to_have_value()
    
1️⃣2️⃣ Count Assertions
    1️⃣ to_have_count()
    Checks number of elements
    Example:
        expect(page.locator(".product")).to_have_count(5)
    Meaning:
        There should be 5 product items.

1️⃣3️⃣ Page Assertions
Playwright can verify page URL and title.
    1️⃣ to_have_url()
    Checks page URL
    Example:
        expect(page).to_have_url("https://example.com/dashboard")
    
    2️⃣ to_have_title()
    Checks page title
    Example:
        expect(page).to_have_title("Dashboard")
    
1️⃣4️⃣ Element Attachment Assertions
    1️⃣ to_be_attached()
    Checks whether element is attached to DOM
    Example:
        expect(page.locator("#login")).to_be_attached()
    
    Meaning:
        Element exists in DOM structure

1️⃣5️⃣ Negating Assertions
Playwright supports negative assertions.
Syntax:
    expect(locator).not_to_ve_visible()

Example:
    expect(page.get_by_text("Error")).not_to_be_visible()

Example:
    expect(page.locator("#loading")).not_to_be_visible()

1️⃣6️⃣ Soft Assertions
Soft assertions allow test to continue even if assertion fails
Example:
    expect(soft(page.get_by_text("login")).to_be_visible())
Use case:
    1. Reporting multiple failures
    2. Non critical checks

1️⃣7️⃣ Hard Assertions vs Soft Assertions
Type & Behavior
---------------
1. Hard assertion -> Test stops when assertion fails
2. Soft assertion -> Test continues even if assertion fails.
Example:
    expect(page.get_by_text("Login")).to_be_visible()

Soft assertion:
    expect.soft(page.get_by_text("Login")).to_be_visible()


